<subSubSection lastPageId="1" lastPageNumber="36" pageId="0" pageNumber="35" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="35">Diagnosis.</paragraph>
<paragraph lastPageId="1" lastPageNumber="36" pageId="0" pageNumber="35">
Small size. Crown of the head strongly elevated above the anterior margin of the pronotum. Ocelli vestigial. Pronotum enlarged, strongly convex, and extended to the scutellar suture. Forewing broad, tectiform, with elongate, sinuate distal segments of veins R and M, closed preapical cells absent. Hind wing with the 
<pageBreakToken pageId="1" pageNumber="36" start="start">submarginal</pageBreakToken>
vein complete and veins RP and MA confluent. First hind tarsomere acuminate. Aedeagus fused to the connective. Female second valvulae asymmetrical.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="1" pageNumber="36" type="distribution">
<paragraph pageId="1" pageNumber="36">Distribution.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="1" pageNumber="36">Oriental region (Fig. 19).</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="1" pageNumber="36" type="remarks">
<paragraph pageId="1" pageNumber="36">Remarks.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="1" pageNumber="36">
This dikraneurine genus is remarkable because it has a feature unknown in other typhlocybinae but present in another leafhopper subfamily (
<taxonomicName lsidName="" pageId="1" pageNumber="36" rank="subFamily" subFamily="Signoretiinae">Signoretiinae</taxonomicName>
), i.e. the elongate pronotum. A full description of the genus was given by 
<bibRefCitation author="Viraktamath, CA" journalOrPublisher="Zootaxa" pageId="2" pageNumber="37" pagination="1 - 7" title="A remarkable new genus of Dikraneurini (Hemiptera: Cicadomorpha: Cicadellidae: Typhlocybinae) from Southeast Asia." volume="2931" year="2011">Viraktamath and Dietrich (2011)</bibRefCitation>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
